onymous creators and copyists in a huge range of centres emerge as active participants in shaping and re-shaping the ideals of their world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCarolingians. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAlcuin.  aAmalarius.  aCharlemagne.  aChrodegang.  aFemale monasticism.  aLiturgical studies.  aLouis the Pious.  aManuscript studies.  aMedieval Latin.  aMedieval heresy.1 aGrifoni, Cinzia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLing, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMitalaité, Kristina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRembold, Ingrid, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRembold, Ingrid, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRose, Els, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVocino, Giorgia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWestwell, Arthur, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWestwell, Arthur, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 avan Renswoude, Irene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 avan Rhijn, Carine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 avan Rhijn, Carine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152614956540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526149565423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526149565/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles